What are Bastian Hosts in AWS ?

- Acts a secure entry point and is connected + has access to all other private subnets 

- Bastian Host security group must allow  inbound from internet (port 22) from restricted CIDR IP ( i.e company IP )
- Security group of EC2 instance must allow the Bastian Host security group to connect 

→  Virtual private cloud → create a public + private subnet 
→ Launch Bastian Host EC2 instance (public IP) in public subnet
→SSH into Public facing Bastian Host ( can access the internet )
→ then SSH into the private EC2 instance (private subnet) (database / internal apps ) that has no internet access


Alternatives ?

→ Can put Bastian Host in private subnet 
→  access these resources in the private subnet through VPN / AWS private link 


What is a NAT Gatway in AWS ? 

AWS service that allows instances ( i.e EC2’s ) in private subnet to initiate outbound internet connect - downloading updates from WWW

Private subnet →  ( route table ) NAT GW ( sits in public subnet) →  Internet Gateway →  WWW

Private instances in private subnet send request to NAT Gateway 
→  NAT Gateway forwards request to internet using NAT public IP  
→  return traffic comes back 
→  private instances stay hidden and not exposed to internet 

+ instances in private subnet can connect to internet whilst blocked from incoming internet traffic 
+ NATGW is created in a specific availability zone ( resilience so create multiple ) + elastic IP ( traffic always knows where to return to - fixed )
+ no security group management 
+ pay per hour 


Nat Gateway for High availability architecture  ? 

→  Nat Gateway created in a specific Availablity zone and uses an elastic IP 
→  1 Nat Gateway per EC2 instance per Subnet 

Best practice to create NAT Gateway in 2 availability zones for high availability and resilience 

AWS region →  VPC →  AZ- A ( private subnet ( EC2 instance ) + public ( NATGW ) ) →  Router →  Internet Gateway →   WWW
                                     → AZ- B ( private subnet ( EC2 instance ) + public ( NATGW ) ) →  Router →  Internet Gateway →   WWW



NAT Gateway ( auto ) vs NAT instance ( manual ) in AWS ?

→ Both allow private instances have access to the internet + have access to public / private IP’s

→ NAT instance however gives you more granular control 
= at the cost of having to monitor availability , scaling , security groups etc 

+ can use it as a Bastian Host where u can’t with a NAT Gateway 

– But NATGW can manage 100gb bandwidth so scales auto where as NAT instance doesn’t 




Network access control List ?

NACL - filter at the (Subnet level) that checks whether traffic should be allowed or denied   based on rules defined 

→  Like a firewall which controls traffic from & to subnets 
→ NACL is a great way to block specific IP addresses at subnet level 
→ 1 NACL per subnet 
→ New subnets are assigned default NACL and will deny everything 

+ NACL rules go from #1-#32766 
+ lower number takes priority 
+ #100 says allow and #200 says deny = allow 
+ last rule is an asterisks * to deny request if no rule found 

AWS region  →VPC → NACL connected to subnets  ( private subnet ( (security groups attached to instances) EC2 instance ) + public ( NATGW ) ) 
                                                                                                                 AZ-A


Inbound traffic :

NACL are attached at the subnet level and are checked first regardless of inbound / outbound  (stateless)= have to specifically define what can go in/out 

Security groups ( that are attached to instances ) then second (stateful )= remembers traffic so if it’s let in , it can go out 



Virtual private cloud (VPC) Peering in AWS ?

A direct connection between 2 or more VPC’s - without the need over going over the public internet 
→  once peered - resources in different VPC’s can communicate using private IP’s

+ used when you have multiple VPC’s in different regions / accounts and want to share data 
+ no overlapping CIDR 
+ make them behave like they’re in the same network 

VPC Peering isn’t Transitive  = VPC A - VPC B   but VPC A can’t talk to VPC C directly , so you need a direct peering of A & C
  
+ must update route table for VPC subnets so EC2 Instances can communicate with each other 



VPC peering between accounts / regions inn AWS ?

→ you can create VPC peering between accounts / regions 
→ you can reference a Security group in a peered VPC ( works across accounts but have to be in same region ) 

Example: connection between 2 VPC’s 
1. Create VPC for one and two ( each VPC has own CIDR block so set of IPv4’s )
2. Create VPC peering request 
3. Accept peering request 
4. Update route tables (using same CIDR block )
5. Configure Network access control list & security groups ( allow port access )
6. Resources can communicate over private IP and controlled environment
